<paragraph id="893436C9E03FFFD5FF44FA2FFC1A17A0" blockId="1.[178,969,1483,1505]" box="[178,969,1483,1505]" pageId="1" pageNumber="802">
<heading id="D27C81A5E03FFFD5FF44FA2FFC1A17A0" box="[178,969,1483,1505]" fontSize="8" level="2" pageId="1" pageNumber="802" reason="2">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03FFFD5FF44FA2FFC5217A1" bold="true" box="[178,897,1483,1505]" pageId="1" pageNumber="802">
Description of the gynandromorph of 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03FFFD5FDBAFA2FFCD217A0" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[588,769,1483,1505]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="802" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03FFFD5FDBAFA2FFCD217A0" bold="true" box="[588,769,1483,1505]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="802">Holopyga fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(FABRICIUS
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03FFFD5FC78FA2FFC1A17A0" bold="true" box="[910,969,1483,1505]" pageId="1" pageNumber="802">1781)</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C1916542E03FFFD6FF44FA11FD7C116F" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="803" pageId="1" pageNumber="802" type="description">
<paragraph id="893436C9E03FFFD5FF44FA11FE42144A" blockId="1.[178,401,1525,1547]" box="[178,401,1525,1547]" pageId="1" pageNumber="802">Body length: 6.2 mm.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="893436C9E03FFFD6FF44F9FFFF291327" blockId="1.[178,1084,1563,1585]" lastBlockId="2.[178,1085,219,358]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="803" pageId="1" pageNumber="802">
Head. General appearance female-like (
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03FFFD5FDABF9FFFD6F1471" box="[605,700,1563,1585]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[178,211,1313,1335]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1: Holopyga fervida, head and mesosoma: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male; (C) female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004381" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004381/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="802">Figs. 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03FFFD5FD38F9FFFD231470" box="[718,752,1563,1585]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[178,211,1533,1555]" captionTargetBox="[225,1036,213,1512]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[224,1039,212,1512]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2: Holopyga fervida, habitus: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male, normal colour; (C) female, normal colour; (D) female, green variation; (E) male, holotype of H. fervida var. taorminensis; (F) male, holotype of H. fervida var. violacea. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="802">2A</figureCitation>
). Red-purple, with blue scapal basin. Frons, vertex, gena, face between eye, and scapal basin with tiny and shallow punctures, 1-3 puncture diameters apart, separated by polished interstices; scapal basin asetose and smooth; ocellar-triangle isosceles; postocellar line distinct and deep; antennae 13-segmented; in dorsal view, angular margins of the head (temples) as acute angles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="893436C9E03CFFD6FF44FE92FCB710F1" blockId="2.[178,1086,373,689]" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">
Mesosoma. Female-like, except for a male mosaic area on pronotum. Pronotum medially divided into a left masculine and a right feminine part (
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03CFFD6FD18FE77FC9A13E9" box="[750,841,403,425]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[178,211,1313,1335]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1: Holopyga fervida, head and mesosoma: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male; (C) female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004381" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004381/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">Figs. 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03CFFD6FCA3FE77FCAB13E8" box="[853,888,403,425]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[178,211,1533,1555]" captionTargetBox="[225,1036,213,1512]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[224,1039,212,1512]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2: Holopyga fervida, habitus: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male, normal colour; (C) female, normal colour; (D) female, green variation; (E) male, holotype of H. fervida var. taorminensis; (F) male, holotype of H. fervida var. violacea. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004383/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">2A</figureCitation>
). The most evident difference is colour: the left side is emerald green as typical for males, in contrast with the red-purple colouration of the female body. Yet, the punctation of this area is critical for a sexual assignment: male punctation is coarser, with larger punctures closer, and micropunctate on interstices, whereas the female's pronotum has sparser punctures, without micropunctation on interstices, but with smooth intervals (comp. 
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03CFFD6FC4DFDC1FBD3107D" box="[955,1024,549,572]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[178,211,1313,1335]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1: Holopyga fervida, head and mesosoma: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male; (C) female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004381" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004381/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
B-C). Mesoscutum, mesoscutellum, metanotum, propodeum, and mesopleuron female-like, with mesoscutum and mesoscutellum red-purple, the latter largely impunctate and apically with large punctures, with greenish-blue bottom; mesopleuron, metanotum, and propodeum dark blue, metanotum with foveate-reticulate punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="893436C9E03CFFD6FF44FD24FD7C116F" blockId="2.[178,1086,704,814]" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">Metasoma. Female-like, terga red-purple, sterna brownish. Terga evenly punctate, with small punctures about one puncture diameter apart; laterally with denser punctures. Apical margin of metasomal terga impunctate or shallowly punctate, brownish; apex of third metasomal tergum with raised brownish rim.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DDF46641E03CFFD6FF44FAC5FC391779" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004381" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4004381" box="[178,1002,1313,1336]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004381/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="803" startId="2.[178,211,1313,1335]" targetBox="[178,1085,869,1297]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="893436C9E03CFFD6FF44FAC5FC391779" blockId="2.[178,1002,1313,1336]" box="[178,1002,1313,1336]" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03CFFD6FF44FAC5FF231777" bold="true" box="[178,240,1313,1335]" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">Fig. 1:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03CFFD6FF03FAC6FE471776" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[245,404,1314,1335]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="803" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03CFFD6FF03FAC6FE471776" box="[245,404,1314,1335]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">Holopyga fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, head and mesosoma: (
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03CFFD6FD9CFAC5FDA91777" bold="true" box="[618,634,1313,1334]" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">A</emphasis>
) gynandromorph; (
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03CFFD6FCDAFAC6FCE81776" bold="true" box="[812,827,1314,1335]" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">B</emphasis>
) male; (
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03CFFD6FC7EFAC5FC4B1776" bold="true" box="[904,920,1313,1335]" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">C</emphasis>
) female.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSection id="E0042F22E03CFFD7FE94FA95FE571465" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="804" pageId="2" pageNumber="803" type="multiple">
<subSubSection id="C1916542E03CFFD7FE94FA95FE571465" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="804" pageId="2" pageNumber="803" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="893436C9E03CFFD6FE94FA95FC5E17C8" blockId="2.[354,909,1393,1418]" box="[354,909,1393,1418]" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">
<heading id="D27C81A5E03CFFD6FE94FA95FC5E17C8" bold="true" box="[354,909,1393,1418]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="803" reason="1">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03CFFD6FE94FA95FC5E17C8" bold="true" box="[354,909,1393,1418]" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">
Identification and variability of 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03CFFD6FD38FA95FC5E17C8" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[718,909,1393,1417]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="803" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03CFFD6FD38FA95FC5E17C8" bold="true" box="[718,909,1393,1417]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">Holopyga fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="893436C9E03CFFD7FF44FA42FE2D13E0" blockId="2.[178,1085,1446,1585]" lastBlockId="3.[178,1086,219,417]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="804" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03CFFD6FF44FA42FEB817FA" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[178,363,1446,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="803" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03CFFD6FF44FA42FEB817FA" box="[178,363,1446,1467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="803">Holopyga fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a typical example of a strongly sexually dimorphic species of 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03CFFD6FF44FA27FEFC1798" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[178,303,1475,1497]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="803" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysididae</taxonomicName>
, males and females being differently coloured, shaped and sculptured. The female is mostly shiny red-purple, with legs, metanotum, mesopleuron, propodeum, and lower part of head blue; conversely, the male is entirely green to blue-green, sometimes with golden reflections on metasoma and occasionally with golden reflections also on head and mesosoma (
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FE6AFF3FFD8012B1" box="[412,595,219,240]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="fervida" variety="taorminensis">
var. 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FE26FF3FFD8012B1" box="[464,595,219,240]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">taorminensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FDA8FF3FFCF912B1" author="TRAUTMANN W" box="[606,810,219,240]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="321 - 322" refId="ref3889" refString="TRAUTMANN W. (1922): Untersuchungen an einigen Goldwespenformen. - Deuts che Entomologische Zeitschrift 1922: 321 - 322." type="journal article" year="1922">TRAUTMANN, 1922</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03DFFD7FCCFFF3FFC5E12B0" box="[825,909,219,241]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[178,211,1533,1555]" captionTargetBox="[225,1036,213,1512]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[224,1039,212,1512]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2: Holopyga fervida, habitus: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male, normal colour; (C) female, normal colour; (D) female, green variation; (E) male, holotype of H. fervida var. taorminensis; (F) male, holotype of H. fervida var. violacea. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004383/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
). The habitus is different: the metasoma of the female is elongated, whereas that of the male has a regularly rounded posterior margin. The body punctation is also considerably different: the female has small, sparse punctures with polished interstices; the male has a coarse, double punctation, with tiny dots on interstices. Significantly different is the punctation of the mesoscutellum, almost entirely polished in female (
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03DFFD7FCBAFE89FC7113C5" box="[844,930,365,388]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[178,211,1313,1335]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1: Holopyga fervida, head and mesosoma: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male; (C) female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004381" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004381/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
) and densely micropunctate in male (
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03DFFD7FE54FE6FFE2213E0" box="[418,497,395,417]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[178,211,1313,1335]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[178,1085,869,1297]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1: Holopyga fervida, head and mesosoma: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male; (C) female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004381" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004381/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="893436C9E03DFFD7FF44FE54FC1310D2" blockId="3.[178,1085,432,659]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">
In Northern Europe, the male can be confused with 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FD3FFE55FC9B1384" box="[713,840,432,454]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. metallica</emphasis>
DAHLBOM, 1854, but it is recognizable for the coarser and denser metasomal punctation, with interstices smaller than a puncture diameter, whereas in 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FDCDFE0FFD681041" box="[571,699,491,512]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. metallica</emphasis>
the metasoma punctation is fine and sparse (see pictures in 
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FE51FDECFD74105F" author="PAUKKUNEN J &amp; BERG A &amp; SOON V &amp; ODEGAARD F" box="[423,679,520,542]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref3373" refString="PAUKKUNEN J., BERG A., SOON V., ODEGAARD F. &amp; P. ROSA (2015): An illustrated key to the cuckoo wasps (Hymenoptera, Chrysididae) of the Nordic and Baltic countries, with description of a new species. - ZooKeys 548: 1 - 116." type="journal article" year="2015">PAUKKUNEN et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The female of 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FCAAFDEDFC0F105C" box="[860,988,520,542]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. metallica</emphasis>
is easily recognizable because its colour and sculpture are similar to the male. In Eastern Mediterranean countries, the Near East and Middle East 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FD00FDA7FC8D1019" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[758,862,579,600]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FD00FDA7FC8D1019" box="[758,862,579,600]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be confused with 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FF44FD85FEF91034" box="[178,298,608,630]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. buyssoni</emphasis>
MERCET, 1902 (often considered as its eastern subspecies), but both sexes of this species are recognizable by large and coarse punctures on the metasoma.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="893436C9E03DFFD7FF44FD47FE9F119C" blockId="3.[178,1085,675,990]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">
For a very long time, males and females of 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FD8CFD47FCFD10F9" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[634,814,675,696]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FD8CFD47FCFD10F9" box="[634,814,675,696]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Holopyga fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were considered different species because of the remarkable sexual dimorphism. The male had been considered a valid species named either 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FE23FD3AFD9610B2" box="[469,581,734,755]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. curvata</emphasis>
(FÖRSTER, 1853) or 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FCDCFD3AFC6810B3" box="[810,955,733,755]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. chloroidea</emphasis>
(DAHLBOM, 1854). TRAUTMANN' s (1922) hypothesis that 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FD74FD1FFD231151" box="[642,752,763,784]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. curvata</emphasis>
could be the male of 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FC23FD1FFBEE1151" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[981,1085,763,784]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FC23FD1FFBEE1151" box="[981,1085,763,784]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not immediately accepted (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FDC8FCFCFD06116F" author="INVREA F" box="[574,725,792,814]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="13 - 15" refId="ref2900" refString="INVREA F. (1923): Note su alcune Holopyga (Hym. - Chrysididae). - Bollettino della Societa entomologica italiana 55: 13 - 15." type="journal article" year="1923">INVREA, 1923</bibRefCitation>
). Still 
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FCD7FCFCFC27116F" author="LINSENMAIER W" box="[801,1012,792,814]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="1 - 232" refId="ref3082" refString="LINSENMAIER W. (1959): Revision der Familie Chrysididae (Hymenoptera) mit besonderer Berucksichtigung der europaischen Spezies. - Mitteilungen der S chweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 32: 1 - 232." type="journal article" year="1959">LINSENMAIER (1959</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FBF2FCFCFBEA116F" author="LINSENMAIER W" box="[1028,1081,792,814]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="1 - 144" refId="ref3116" refString="LINSENMAIER W. (1968): Revision der Familie Chrysididae (Hymenoptera). Zweiter Nachtrag. - Mitteilungen der Schw eizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 41 (1 - 4): 1 - 144." type="journal article" year="1968">1968</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FF44FCD1FF35110A" author="LINSENMAIER W" box="[178,230,821,843]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="343 - 376" refId="ref3152" refString="LINSENMAIER W. (1969): The chrysid wasps of Palestine (Hym., Chrysididae). A faunistic catalogue with descriptions of new species and forms. - Israel Journal of Entomology 4: 343 - 376." type="journal article" year="1969">1969</bibRefCitation>
) considered 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FE98FCD2FE2D110B" box="[366,510,821,843]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. chloroidea</emphasis>
as the separate subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FCB6FCD2FC79110B" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[832,938,821,843]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FCB6FCD2FC79110B" box="[832,938,821,843]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
distributed in 
<collectingCountry id="F19C7659E03DFFD7FF44FCB7FEF91128" box="[178,298,851,873]" name="Turkey" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Asia Minor</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F19C7659E03DFFD7FEC3FCB7FEBE1128" box="[309,365,851,873]" name="Syria" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Syria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F19C7659E03DFFD7FE8EFCB7FE051128" box="[376,470,851,873]" name="Palestine" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Palestine</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F19C7659E03DFFD7FDFBFCB7FD8A1129" box="[525,601,851,872]" name="Cyprus" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Cyprus</collectingCountry>
. His interpretation, even though not in contrast with the original distribution of 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FDF2FC95FD4711C4" box="[516,660,880,902]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. chloroidea</emphasis>
, was a source of taxonomical instability and for this reason ROSA &amp; XU (2015) designated the 
<typeStatus id="5630886BE03DFFD7FD1BFC69FC9911E2" box="[749,842,909,931]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FC87FC6AFBD211E3" box="[881,1025,909,931]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. chloroidea</emphasis>
. This eastern Mediterranean species with an obvious coarser punctation is currently referred to as 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FF3BFC2DFE96119C" box="[205,325,968,990]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. buyssoni</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="893436C9E03DFFD7FF44FC09FD7716F2" blockId="3.[178,1085,1005,1203]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">
The Paris Museum houses an interesting female specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FCD5FC0AFC591643" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[803,906,1005,1027]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FCD5FC0AFC591643" box="[803,906,1005,1027]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the aberrant colour of a male. It was collected near Paris and erroneously designated as the 
<typeStatus id="5630886BE03DFFD7FC16FBEFFBEE1660" box="[992,1085,1035,1057]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FF26FBCDFEB3167C" box="[208,352,1064,1086]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. chloroidea</emphasis>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FE7AFBCCFDFA167F" author="KIMSEY L" box="[396,553,1064,1086]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="105 - 110" refId="ref3017" refString="KIMSEY L. S. (1986): Designation of chrysidid lectotypes. - The Pan-Pa cific Entomologist 62: 105 - 110." type="journal article" year="1986">KIMSEY (1986)</bibRefCitation>
(see ROSA &amp; XU 2015). A second female of such colour was collected by Fritz Blühweiss in the Danube wetlands (&quot;Donauauen&quot;) in eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F19C7659E03DFFD7FEF7FB87FE981638" box="[257,331,1123,1145]" name="Austria" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Austria</collectingCountry>
(probably in or close to 
<collectingRegion id="4B4FF82BE03DFFD7FDBAFB87FD491638" box="[588,666,1123,1145]" country="Austria" name="Wien" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Vienna</collectingRegion>
). This specimen (
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03DFFD7FCB9FB87FC721638" box="[847,929,1123,1145]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[178,211,1533,1555]" captionTargetBox="[225,1036,213,1512]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[224,1039,212,1512]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2: Holopyga fervida, habitus: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male, normal colour; (C) female, normal colour; (D) female, green variation; (E) male, holotype of H. fervida var. taorminensis; (F) male, holotype of H. fervida var. violacea. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004383/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
), housed at the 
<collectingRegion id="4B4FF82BE03DFFD7FF44FB64FF2816D7" box="[178,251,1152,1174]" country="Austria" name="Wien" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Vienna</collectingRegion>
Museum, has been labelled by Karl Hammer as the type of &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FC7EFB64FEF316F3" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="fervida" variety="viridis">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FC7EFB64FBEE16D4" box="[904,1085,1152,1173]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Holopyga fervida</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FF29FB79FEF316F3" box="[223,288,1181,1202]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">viridis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot;, but it was never formally described.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="893436C9E03DFFD7FF44FB27FC85170F" blockId="3.[178,1086,1219,1358]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FEE2FB27FEAF1699" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[276,380,1219,1240]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FEE2FB27FEAF1699" box="[276,380,1219,1240]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H. fervida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be very variable in colour (
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03DFFD7FD30FB27FCBD1698" box="[710,878,1219,1241]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[178,211,1533,1555]" captionTargetBox="[225,1036,213,1512]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[224,1039,212,1512]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2: Holopyga fervida, habitus: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male, normal colour; (C) female, normal colour; (D) female, green variation; (E) male, holotype of H. fervida var. taorminensis; (F) male, holotype of H. fervida var. violacea. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004383/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Figs 2B, 2E, 2F</figureCitation>
). The typical colour is green, but several specimens from all over Europe are entirely deep blue (
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03DFFD7FC3CFB04FBEA16B7" box="[970,1081,1248,1270]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[178,211,1533,1555]" captionTargetBox="[225,1036,213,1512]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[224,1039,212,1512]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2: Holopyga fervida, habitus: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male, normal colour; (C) female, normal colour; (D) female, green variation; (E) male, holotype of H. fervida var. taorminensis; (F) male, holotype of H. fervida var. violacea. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004383/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">
Fig. 2F, 
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FBD2FB05FBEA16B7" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[1060,1081,1249,1270]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FBD2FB05FBEA16B7" box="[1060,1081,1249,1270]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">H</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</figureCitation>
. fervida violacea HOFFMANN, 1935) or green with golden metasoma. In the southernmost European localities, males can be variably golden red. An extreme colour form was described as 
<emphasis id="BBFFEADBE03DFFD7FEC3FADDFDF6170F" box="[309,549,1336,1358]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">
<taxonomicName id="4E8B4D4AE03DFFD7FEC3FADDFE4F170C" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[309,412,1336,1358]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Holopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fervida">H. fervida</taxonomicName>
taorminensis
</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FDDDFADCFD3D170C" author="TRAUTMANN W" box="[555,750,1336,1357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="321 - 322" refId="ref3889" refString="TRAUTMANN W. (1922): Untersuchungen an einigen Goldwespenformen. - Deuts che Entomologische Zeitschrift 1922: 321 - 322." type="journal article" year="1922">TRAUTMANN, 1922</bibRefCitation>
(
<figureCitation id="11B02A4CE03DFFD7FD0DFADCFC99170F" box="[763,842,1336,1358]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[178,211,1533,1555]" captionTargetBox="[225,1036,213,1512]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[224,1039,212,1512]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2: Holopyga fervida, habitus: (A) gynandromorph; (B) male, normal colour; (C) female, normal colour; (D) female, green variation; (E) male, holotype of H. fervida var. taorminensis; (F) male, holotype of H. fervida var. violacea. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004383/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="893436C9E03DFFD7FF44FAB9FE571465" blockId="3.[178,1085,1373,1572]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804">
The specimen here described as a gynandromorph shows the left half of the pronotum green and with coarse and double punctation, referable to a phenotypic trait of the male, while all other features are that of a female. The aberrant character of this specimen is very obvious. The authors presently do not have an explanation why gynandromorphism is so rare in cuckoo wasps, compared to some other families of Aculeata like spider wasps or bees, where this phenomenon is more frequently observed (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FC43FA14FBEA1447" author="WAHIS R" box="[949,1081,1520,1542]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="547 - 551" refId="ref4049" refString="WAHIS R. (1996): Un gynandromorphe d' Anoplius viaticus (LINNAEUS) et deux cas de monstruosite chez Priocnemis minuta (VANDER LINDEN) et Priocnemis susterai HAUPT (Hymenoptera, Pompilidae). - Li nzer biologische Beitrage 28 (1): 547 - 551." type="journal article" year="1996">WAHIS 1996</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="ED1A4B38E03DFFD7FF44F9EAFEAB1465" author="MICHEZ D &amp; RASMONT P &amp; TERZO M" box="[178,376,1549,1572]" pageId="3" pageNumber="804" pagination="365 - 375" refId="ref3262" refString="MICHEZ D., RASMONT P., TERZO M. &amp; N. J. VEREECKEN (2009): A synthesis of gynandromorphy among wild bees (Hymenoptera: Apoidea), with an annotated description of several new cases. - Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France 45 (3): 365 - 375." type="journal article" year="2009">MICHEZ et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
